My First Sweet R Markdown Notebook

C.M. Gienger

2022-11-09

This is an example of an R Markdown Notebook. When you execute code within the notebook, the results appear beneath the code. This allows you to have a linear workflow, which will help you collaborate with others more efficiently. The basics of R Markdown can be found here. There is also a cheatsheet in the RStudio help menu.

First, lets make a simple graph using some base R code.

model_1 <- lm(dist ~ speed, data = cars)
plot(dist ~ speed, data = cars)
abline(model_1)

Next, we can fit a linear model.

model_2 <- lm(dist ~ speed, data = cars)
anova(model_2)

Lets make a table that summarizes the diamond data.

summary1 <- summarise(group_by(diamonds, cut),
          n=n(), 
          mean=mean(price),
          sd=sd(price))  
kable(summary1, caption = 'Table 2. A summary kable displaying number, mean, and standard deviation for each of five cuts of diamond.', digits = c(0, 0, 1, 1))

Lets insert a static image, like a picture or figure. Notice that this is inline code, not inside a code chunk.

Figure 1. Geographic distribution of the Gila Monster (Heloderma suspectum)

Lets make a simple map for our report.

leaflet() %>%
  setView(-87.354841, 36.534942, zoom = 16) %>% #lat-long of the place of interest
  addTiles() %>%
  addMarkers(-87.354841, 36.534942, popup = "APSU")
